subSubSection.paragraph:
Second pereiopods (
Figs 2E
; 
3D
) short, subequal in length to third maxilliped. Ischium and merus elongate; carpus five-segmented, distal segment longest, segment length ratio (proximal to distal) 1.0:0.5:0.5:0.6:1.2. Dactylus (
Figs 2F
; 
3E
) short, beak-like; 
0.15 in
length of propodus; terminating in small spine; fixed finger terminating in two blunt spines; fingers with distal tufts of plumose setae.

Third pereiopod (
Fig. 2G
) robust; ischium with two spines on inferior margin; merus unarmed, provided with row of short, simple setae on mesial margin, 2.1 times length of ischium; carpus unarmed, equal in length to ischium; propodus armed with eight spines along inferior margin and two spines mediodistally, equal in length to merus; dactylus (
Figs 2H
; 
3F
) slightly curved, approximately 0.25 times length of propodus, unguis clearly demarcated, serrated on inferior margin, not biunguiculate.

Fourth and fifth pereiopods similar to third, unguis (
Fig. 2I
) serrated on inferior margin, not biunguiculate; fifth pereiopod more slender.
